> osborne1@muvms6.wvnet.edu writes:

[Stuff Deleted]
 
>>There are, however, lots of various algorhithms for pseudorandom
>>functions.   A pseudorandom function is one that, (in theory),
>>for every x, f(x) is basically unpredictable, except for a given
>>range.  To be useful, it should at least pass a chi square
>>statistical attack.
> 
> Does it really need to pass a chi square test? I am assuming you are
> comparing the output of the function to an uniform distribution using
> chi square as the figure of merit. What I am wondering is if I have a
> "suitably unpredictable" function, isn't this good enough whether or
> not the chi square value (based on an uniform distribution) is met?

I admit, I am a perfectionist.

> 
> I am thinking maybe a better test for a pseudo random function output
> would be the correlation between sequential values over some useful span
> Clearly, the correlation between the nth byte and the next byte is not
> a good enough test.

Chi square, as you mentined, bases its results over the whole distribution.
For whatever security reasons I would need it for, I'd go for the BEST
random function I could get...
Assuming you're doing something beyond some random function for a game.
